<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<FindBugsFilter xmlns="https://github.com/spotbugs/filter/3.0.0">
  <!--
    The baseline (Chapter 39, lever 3: freeze the findings that exist TODAY so the gate reacts only to
    CHANGE). A SpotBugs excludeFilterFile excludes any finding matched by a <Match> from the report, so a
    <Match> scoped to the legacy class freezes the legacy finding without freezing anything else. This is
    the precondition for turning a gate on over a noisy codebase at all: the build goes green not because
    the debt is gone, but because the past is frozen and only new findings can fail it.

    The honest edge the chapter names: a baseline that freezes a finding also freezes any real bug hiding
    behind the same match, and the team stops seeing it. The match is therefore kept as narrow as the bug
    pattern allows (one class, the named patterns), and it is version-controlled here so it shows up in
    PRs and can be reviewed and periodically retired — debt about debt, not a place to hide findings.

    Note the division of labour with the source-level control: the one reviewed FALSE POSITIVE is NOT
    listed here. It is suppressed at its exact site with @SuppressFBWarnings(value, justification) in
    PriceFormatter, so the reason travels with the code. This file holds only the legacy baseline, so the
    two kinds of silencing (a frozen past vs. a judged false positive) stay visibly distinct.
  -->

  <!--
    Legacy baseline. LegacyPriceTable predates the gate and exposes its internal mutable array directly
    from rawTiers(), so at this module's threshold (Low/Max) SpotBugs raises EI_EXPOSE_REP (and the
    store-side EI_EXPOSE_REP2 for the array taken in via the constructor). The finding is real debt, not a
    false positive — the right long-term fix is the defensive copy the clean PricingCatalog already makes
    (Arrays.copyOf / List.copyOf), and this baseline DEFERS that fix rather than pretending it is done.
    Verified load-bearing: with this <Match> removed the SpotBugs gate goes red on LegacyPriceTable.
    EI_EXPOSE_REP is a real pattern in the pinned engine (category MALICIOUS_CODE). The clean class is
    untouched here, so a NEW EI_EXPOSE_REP added to PricingCatalog is reported and fails the build — the
    ratchet the chapter describes.
  -->
  <Match>
    <Class name="org.acme.findings.LegacyPriceTable"/>
    <!-- tag::baseline-match[] -->
    <Bug pattern="EI_EXPOSE_REP,EI_EXPOSE_REP2"/>
    <!-- end::baseline-match[] -->
  </Match>
</FindBugsFilter>
